	<div class=3D"message-userContent lbContainer js-lbContainer " data-lb-id=
=3D"post-16291265" data-lb-caption-desc=3D"TripleATeam =C2=B7 Apr 7, 2022 a=
t 11:01 AM">

	=09

		<article class=3D"message-body js-selectToQuote">
		=09
			=09
		=09

			<div itemprop=3D"text">
			=09
					<div class=3D"bbWrapper">Elo isn't an acronym.<br>
<br>
Elo works by giving each player a rating, assuming that they come into the =
game with 1000 points worth of skill. If you can beat someone with 1000 poi=
nts of skill 50% of the time, you also have 1000 points. If you can beat so=
meone with 1000 points 60% of the time, you have 1072 points. Since the rat=
ing is an approximation, after every game the ratings are reassessed. <br>
<br>
If you had a 10% chance of losing to someone rated 1000 and you did, you'll=
 lose a lot of points and they'll gain a lot for upsetting you. It's a larg=
e correction since Bayesian statistics suggests you were overrated and/or t=
hey were underrated. The idea is you'll always be converging on your new va=
lue.<br>
<br>
Some critics dislike elo since high-level players reach a sort of ceiling a=
nd cannot progress in elo unless their opponents also gain points. In chess=
, currently, Magnus Carlsen loses tons of points for losses and only gains =
a few for wins, making increasing his rating near-impossible. Additionally,=
 the only way for elo to "leave" the system is by players retiring. There i=
s no guarantee that the entrants into the system will lose exactly the same=
 amount of points as those leaving.<br>
<br>
This has led to what people consider an "inflation" of elo. The suggestion =
is, on average, those that retire do so at a ranking lower they came in wit=
h, which leads to extra elo points in the system over the years, which natu=
rally congregates at the top. As such, players of today have much higher el=
os than their equally-skilled counterparts of decades ago. Elo should gener=
ally be used with contemporaries, not with historical comparisons.<br>
<br>
Lastly, by design, elo is slow to change. It converges on a solution and re=
quires that many matches are played and in similar conditions. This is nece=
ssary to converge. Perfect for games like chess, less so for those like ten=
nis, with 3 surfaces and many different conditions, plus few matches to boo=
t. This might make players have elo that more reflects them at some point i=
n the past rather than their current state.</div>
			=09
