			<div itemprop=3D"text">
			=09
					<div class=3D"bbWrapper">In tennis, Elo can't distinguish between a Sl=
am and a 250 and weighs each win or loss as the same.  That's it biggest fl=
aw when used in tennis in my opinion.  It's second biggest flaw is that bec=
ause tennis is played on 3 or 4 different surfaces, depends on the era, the=
 weighted rating is flawed because it takes into account all surfaces, with=
 all tournaments rated the same, which gives the impression one player had =
a higher peak across the entire tour than someone far better and accomplish=
ed.  This is why surface Elo is the one that is closest to the truth.<br>
<br>
However, it has too many coincidences to say it's all fodder.  Elo says the=
 Federer/Nadal/Djokovic/Murray/Wawrinka era and the Borg/McEnroe/Connors/Le=
ndl/Wilander eras are the two most competitive and highest quality eras in =
the Open Era.  How far off is that?  Because of that, Djokovic, Borg and Mc=
Enroe have the highest peaks because they dominated strong eras.  Nadal and=
 Federer come in 4th and 5th. How far off is this?</div>
			=09
			</div>

