			=09
					<div class=3D"bbWrapper"><blockquote data-attributes=3D"member: 739484=
" data-quote=3D"NoleFam" data-source=3D"post: 16291457" class=3D"bbCodeBloc=
k bbCodeBlock--expandable bbCodeBlock--quote js-expandWatch is-expandable">
=09
		<div class=3D"bbCodeBlock-title">
		=09
				<a href=3D"https://tt.tennis-warehouse.com/index.php?goto/post&amp;id=
=3D16291457" class=3D"bbCodeBlock-sourceJump" rel=3D"nofollow" data-xf-clic=
k=3D"attribution" data-content-selector=3D"#post-16291457">NoleFam said:</a=
>
		=09
		</div>
=09
	<div class=3D"bbCodeBlock-content">
	=09
		<div class=3D"bbCodeBlock-expandContent js-expandContent ">
			In tennis, Elo can't distinguish between a Slam and a 250 and weighs eac=
h win or loss as the same.  That's it biggest flaw when used in tennis in m=
y opinion.  It's second biggest flaw is that because tennis is played on 3 =
or 4 different surfaces, depends on the era, the weighted rating is flawed =
because it takes into account all surfaces, with all tournaments rated the =
same, which gives the impression one player had a higher peak across the en=
tire tour than someone far better and accomplished.  This is why surface El=
o is the one that is closest to the truth.<br>
<br>
However, it has too many coincidences to say it's all fodder.  Elo says the=
